EXG Bio-Amp Pill BLE Monitor System
ESP32-S3 Based Wireless Physiological Signal Acquisition

Author: RAKESH KANABUR
Hardware: ESP32-S3 Dev Module + Bio-Amp EXG Pill

PROJECT OVERVIEW
This project implements a wireless biosignal acquisition system using the Bio-Amp EXG Pill (an open-source electrophysiology module) connected to an ESP32-S3 Dev Module. 
The system captures electromyography (EMG), electrocardiography (ECG), 
or other biopotential signals and transmits them via Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) to any compatible receiver (smartphone, PC, or another ESP32).


Key Features
125 Hz sampling rate

4-channel signal transmission

BLE Notify characteristic for real-time data streaming

Digital filtering (IIR bandpass 0.5-100 Hz)

12-bit ADC resolution

11 dB signal attenuation for biopotential range

OTA (Over-The-Air) update capable

Serial debug output at 115200 baud



Applications
Wearable health monitoring

Prosthetic control (EMG)

Heart rate monitoring (ECG)

Muscle activity tracking

Research and education


HARDWARE REQUIREMENTS
2.1 Components List
Component	Quantity	Purpose
ESP32-S3 Dev Module	1	Main microcontroller & BLE transmitter
Bio-Amp EXG Pill	1	Biopotential signal acquisition
Electrodes (Ag/AgCl)	3	Signal pickup (Active, Reference, Ground)
3.7V Li-Po Battery (400mAh+)	1	Portable power
Jumper Wires (F-F, M-F)	10	Connections
USB-C Cable	1	Programming & charging
Shielded Cables	3	Noise reduction for electrode leads

Bio-Amp EXG Pill Specifications
Input Voltage: 2.9V - 5.5V

Gain: 1000x (configurable via resistors)

Bandwidth: 0.5 Hz - 250 Hz (ECG/EMG optimized)

CMRR: > 110 dB

Input Noise: < 1 µV RMS

Output: Analog voltage (0-3.3V)




